<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-808-974  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 808 974.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Lan Times  Sept 1989 v6 n9 p148(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The ARCNET protocol: a survivor's tale. (includes related articleson history of ARCNET's protocol and on frames)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Connor, Deni.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>ARCNET is a long-established networking access method that has amarket share of about 20 percent of installed local area networks.andO;ARCNET provides a transmission rate of only 2.5M-bps but isextremely reliable.andP;  The ARCNET protocol is based upon a frame, apacket of data, referred to as an invitation-to-transmit (ITT).andP;  Aworkstation holding the ITT is able to transmit frames to otherworkstations.andP;  Only one ITT travels the wire, so workstations donot have to contend for access.andP;  When the frame has transmitted,the workstation holding the ITT hands it on to the workstationwith the next logical address.andP;  The logical address can correspondto physical location or be randomly assigned.andP;  Token-ring is theother common token-passing method.andP;  Examples are discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   Datapoint ARCnet (Local area network) (design and construction).andO;Topic:     ProtocolAnalysisReliabilityTransmission SpeedNetworks.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   A network manager can assign logical addresses in a randomfashion.... (chart)The ITT passes from logical address to logical address.... (chart)In receiver mode, three things can occur. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>